START: Analyze script design and impact on process spawning
=== Script Analysis ===
SCRIPT ANALYSIS: Do Watchdog Scripts Cause Process Spawning?

1. SCRIPT OPERATIONS (All bash-only, NO external commands):
   ✓ Read/write file operations only
   ✓ Bash string pattern matching only ([[ ]] conditionals)
   ✓ Bash builtins only (no grep, ps, pgrep, cat, etc.)
   ✓ Exit codes returned (no process spawning)

2. What Each Script Does:
   • terminal-watchdog.sh: Reads .log file, checks for markers, exits
   • pre-response-check.sh: Reads .log file, checks markers, exits
   • pre-stop-watchdog.sh: Reads .log file, checks markers, exits

3. Impact on Process Tree:
   ❌ NO zygote spawning - Scripts use only bash builtins
   ❌ NO terminal spawning - Scripts don't call system commands
   ❌ NO child processes - No external process execution
   ✓ Minimal overhead - Just bash string operations

4. Where Terminals/Zygotes Actually Come From:
   ✅ Terminals (pts) - Spawned by VS Code terminal feature
   ✅ Zygotes - Spawned by VS Code main process for sandboxing
   ✅ Extensions - Loaded by VS Code extension host (PID 3276746)
   ✓ NOT the watchdog scripts

5. Terminal Count in Process Tree (from previous check):
   • pts/0 through pts/8 = 9 terminal instances
   • These are created by VS Code's built-in terminal, NOT scripts
   • Scripts are ONLY called within these terminals (not spawning them)

CONCLUSION: The .augment/ watchdog scripts DO NOT cause:
   ❌ Zygote process spawning
   ❌ Additional terminal spawning
   ❌ Resource consumption beyond bash string operations
   ✅ They are deliberately designed with "bash builtins ONLY" requirement
END: Analysis complete
